<br><strong>Small Group Sharing and Interpretation</strong><br>Divide students into small groups (3-4 students).<br>Each group discusses the collaboratively written cinquain poems. Ask guiding questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>What are the key ideas or images that emerged in our poems?</li>\n<li>How do the different lines connect to the concept of global partnerships and the targets of Global Goal 17?</li>\n<li>Were there any surprising or unexpected word choices that created interesting meanings?</li>\n<li>What overall message about working together for sustainable development do our poems convey?</li>\n</ul><br><strong>Reflection and Summary</strong><br>Have students reflect on their learning experience through discussion or writing.<br>Ask guiding questions like:\n<ul>\n<li>How did the structured yet collaborative nature of the cinquain help us to explore the complexities of global partnerships in a concise way?</li>\n<li>What did you learn about the power of single words and short phrases to convey big ideas related to collaboration, resources, or technology transfer?</li>\n<li>Did the process of building a poem line by line, with each student contributing without knowing the full outcome, surprise you? How does this reflect real-world partnerships?</li>\n<li>How did working together tgo create these poems enhance your understanding of the importance of listening and building upon others’ ideas?</li>\n<li>What did you discover about your own creative contributions when working within a very specific poetic framework?</li>\n<li>What new insights did you gain about Global Goal 17 and the critical importance of strengthening global partnerships for sustainable development through this activity?</li>\n<li>How did the words and themes that emerged in our cinquains highlight different facets or challenges related to Global Goal 17 (e.g., financial aid, technology sharing, capacity building, trade)?</li>\n<li>Did the activity make you think differently about who needs to partner to solve global problems and why their diverse contributions are essential?</li>\n<li>What common themes or powerful messages about unity, cooperation, or the future emerged across the different cinquains we created?</li>\n<li>How can ev en a short, collaboratively written poem help to advocate for the goals of international cooperation?</li>\n<li>Did creating these poems spark any personal connection or reflections on your own experiences with teamwork, compromise, or shared goals?</li>\n<li>What emotions or motivations did you connect with during this lesson, and how might those inspire you to take action related to global partnerships?</li>\n<li>How has this lesson influenced your thinking about your own role in fostering cooperation in your daily life or community?</li>\n</ul><br><strong>Assessment</strong>\n<ul>\n<li>Consistent and enthusiastic involvement in all phases of the lesson, including the initial brainstorming, understanding cinquain structure, the collaborative writing process, and active participation in discussions.</li>\n<li>Comprehension of Global Goal 17 themes (e.g., financial resources, technology transfer, capacity building, multi-stakeholder partnerships) as demonstrated through word choices and the overall meaning of the collaboratively written cinquains.</li>\n<li>Originality and effectiveness in contributing to cinquains that adhere to the established word-count structure (1-2-3-4-1), while still conveying meaningful content related to Global Goal 17.</li>\n<li>How clearly and powerfully the collaboratively written cinquains communicate the intended message about Global Goal 17. Did the concise form successfully evoke thought or emotion related to global partnerships?</li>\n<li>Ability to work effectively as a class, contributing ideas for each line, listening to and building upon classmates’ suggestions, and collaboration cohesively to complete the poems.</li>\n<li>Ability to articulate the connections between the cinquains and Global Goal 17 themes, and to provide thoughtful feedback on the poems.</li>\n<li>Nuance and epth of understanding demonstrated in reflections, particularly concerning the role of concise creative writing and collective creation in advocating for global partnerships.</li>\n</ul>"} {sdgColor} />

